  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hydration is key; calculate it right, or risk a fright!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 1550 ml. This is determined by applying the Holliday-Segar formula for maintenance fluid calculation, which accounts for metabolic water requirements based on body weight.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Holliday-Segar formula is a widely accepted method for estimating daily maintenance fluid requirements in pediatric patients. It is based on the principle that fluid needs correlate with energy expenditure, which in turn correlates with body weight. The formula calculates 100 ml/kg for the first 10 kg, 50 ml/kg for the next 10 kg, and 20 ml/kg for every kilogram thereafter. For a 22-kg infant, this translates to (10 kg * 100 ml/kg) + (10 kg * 50 ml/kg) + (2 kg * 20 ml/kg) = 1000 ml + 500 ml + 40 ml = 1540 ml, which is approximated by option C.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1100 ml is significantly lower than the calculated maintenance fluid requirement for a 22-kg infant, potentially leading to dehydration.\nOption B (Incorrect): 1250 ml is below the calculated maintenance fluid requirement for a 22-kg infant, risking inadequate hydration.\nOption D (Incorrect): 1700 ml is higher than the calculated maintenance fluid requirement, potentially leading to fluid overload.\nOption E (Incorrect): 1850 ml is significantly higher than the calculated maintenance fluid requirement, increasing the risk of fluid overload and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Weight Range | Fluid Requirement (Holliday-Segar) | Calculation Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| First 10 kg | 100 ml/kg/day | 8 kg infant: 800 ml/day |\n| Next 10 kg (11-20 kg) | 50 ml/kg/day | 15 kg infant: 1000 ml (for 10 kg) + 250 ml (for 5 kg) = 1250 ml/day |\n| > 20 kg | 20 ml/kg/day | 22 kg infant: 1000 ml + 500 ml + 40 ml = 1540 ml/day |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Use Holliday-Segar: 100-50-20 rule for pediatric maintenance fluids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable. This question pertains to fluid calculation, not imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline (2018): While the Holliday-Segar method remains the standard for calculating maintenance fluid *volume*, the AAP recommends isotonic intravenous fluids (e.g., 0.9% sodium chloride with dextrose) for maintenance in most hospitalized children, rather than hypotonic solutions, to reduce the risk of hyponatremia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | 1100 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | 1250 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | 1550 ml | ✅ Correct |\n| d | 1700 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | 1850 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c) Maintenance water and electrolyte requirements are illustrated in the table indicated below. The vol** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
