  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's: The great mimicker of acute abdominal pathology.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAll options represent classic clinical presentations of a Meckel's diverticulum, the most common congenital anomaly of the GI tract. Its varied presentations stem from its embryological origin and potential for ectopic tissue, making it a significant cause of acute abdominal pathology in children.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum is a remnant of the omphalomesenteric (vitelline) duct, connecting the fetal midgut to the yolk sac. Its diverse clinical manifestations, including hemorrhage (due to ectopic gastric mucosa causing ulceration), obstruction (intussusception, volvulus, or adhesions), diverticulitis (inflammation often mimicking appendicitis), and umbilical fistulas (from a persistent patent duct), reflect the potential for complications arising from this vestigial structure. Symptomatic cases often present in childhood, with about half occurring before age 2.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options (A, B, C, D, E) are correct as they represent well-documented clinical presentations of a Meckel's diverticulum, as detailed in the provided text.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Presentation | Mechanism | Approximate Frequency (%) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hemorrhage | Ectopic gastric mucosa causing ulceration | 30-35 |\n| Small Bowel Obstruction | Intussusception, Volvulus, Adhesions | 30-35 |\n| Diverticulitis | Inflammation, often mimicking appendicitis | 20-25 |\n| Umbilical Fistula | Persistent patent omphalomesenteric duct | 10 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The 'Rule of 2s' for Meckel's: 2% incidence, 2 feet from ileocecal valve, 2 inches long, 2 types of ectopic tissue, symptomatic by age 2.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a Meckel's diverticulum can be challenging to visualize directly. A Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan (Meckel's scan) is used to detect ectopic gastric mucosa. Intraoperatively, it appears as an antimesenteric diverticulum, typically 2 feet from the ileocecal valve. No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) Clinical Statements. APSA provides clinical guidance on the management of congenital anomalies like Meckel's diverticulum, emphasizing early diagnosis and surgical intervention for symptomatic cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Patent omphalomesenteric duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Right lower quadrant peritoneal findings | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c, d, e) The most frequent congenital anomaly of the GI tract is a Meckel’s diverticulum. The incidence is ab** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
