  "question": "A 3-week old infant has a barium upper gastrointestinal series to evaluate vomiting. The duodenojejunal flexure is found to be to the right of the midline as well as more caudal and anterior than a normal ligament of Treitz. The child is seen to reflux barium spontaneously to the level of the mid-thoracic esophagus. You would recommend which of the following?\n\n![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_19.png)",
  "options": {
    "A": "Barium enema",
    "B": "Emergency laparotomy",
    "C": "A trial of H2, blockade and cisapride therapy",
    "D": "Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy",
    "E": "Overnight pH probe analysis"
  },
  "answer": "b) This child has malrotation and is at risk for midgut volvulus based on the imaging findings. Typically, malrotation produces an incomplete obstruction of the duodenum with a corkscrew or coiled appearance in the third or fourth portions of the duodenum. Malposition of the duodenojejunal junction is diagnostic. In particular, this includes a location to the right of the midline. Additionally, failure to achieve normal posterior and cephalad fixation is typical. The small bowel resides in the right abdomen and the colon and cecum are on the left. Attempts to radiographically differentiate malrotation with or without volvulus are unreliable and therefore hazardous. This child has gastroesophageal reflux which is likely secondary to the partial duodenal obstruction from malrotation. None of the alternatives other than emergency laparotomy are appropriate. There is no role for nonoperative management of malrotation in the neonate. Assessment, resuscitation and preoperative preparation should be conducted concurrently as the child is prepared for laparotomy. This urgency is because a delay measured in hours may represent the difference between a viable or infarcted midgut at laparotomy. Fifty to 75% of malrotations are discovered in the first month of life and about 90% occur in children less than one year of age.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't delay; a twisted gut needs a surgeon's cut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis 3-week-old infant presents with classic upper GI findings indicative of intestinal malrotation: the duodenojejunal flexure is to the right of the midline, caudal, and anterior. This anatomical anomaly places the infant at immediate risk for midgut volvulus, a life-threatening condition requiring emergency laparotomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntestinal malrotation is a congenital anomaly where the normal rotation and fixation of the gut during embryonic development fail. The critical diagnostic finding on an upper GI series is the abnormal position of the ligament of Treitz (duodenojejunal flexure), which should normally be superior, posterior, and to the left of the midline. Its displacement to the right, caudal, and anterior signifies malrotation, creating a narrow mesenteric base that predisposes to midgut volvulus. Volvulus can rapidly lead to bowel ischemia, necrosis, and short gut syndrome, making immediate surgical intervention (Ladd procedure) paramount to prevent catastrophic outcomes. The reported gastroesophageal reflux is likely a secondary symptom of the partial duodenal obstruction caused by the malrotation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Barium enema) (Incorrect): While a barium enema can show cecal position, it is not the primary diagnostic study for malrotation, and it does not address the immediate surgical emergency.\nOption C (A trial of H2, blockade and cisapride therapy) (Incorrect): This is medical management for reflux, which is a secondary symptom. It does not treat the underlying mechanical obstruction and life-threatening risk of volvulus. Cisapride is also rarely used due to cardiac side effects.\nOption D (Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy) (Incorrect): Endoscopy is not the appropriate diagnostic tool for malrotation as it cannot reliably assess the position of the ligament of Treitz or the overall bowel anatomy, nor can it address the surgical emergency.\nOption E (Overnight pH probe analysis) (Incorrect): This test is used to quantify gastroesophageal reflux disease severity and is irrelevant to the diagnosis or urgent management of a mechanical obstruction like malrotation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key UGI Finding | Management | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Malrotation | Duodenojejunal flexure right of midline, caudal, anterior | Emergency Laparotomy (Ladd procedure) | HIGH (hours matter) |\n| Pyloric Stenosis | 'String sign,' 'shoulder sign,' delayed gastric emptying | Pyloromyotomy (urgent, not emergency) | Medium |\n| Duodenal Atresia | 'Double bubble' sign (plain film) | Surgical repair (duodenoduodenostomy) | High (neonatal obstruction) |\n| GERD (typical) | Free reflux, normal anatomy | Medical management, lifestyle changes | Low |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malrotation = abnormal Ligament of Treitz = surgical emergency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe described UGI series findings of the duodenojejunal flexure to the right of the midline, caudal, and anterior are pathognomonic for malrotation. Intraoperatively, one would expect to find a narrow mesenteric base, the small bowel predominantly on the right, the colon on the left, and potentially Ladd's bands crossing and obstructing the duodenum. The image tag `![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_19.png)` refers to the visual representation of these UGI findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) Position Statement on the Management of Malrotation (2019): Recommends prompt surgical intervention (Ladd procedure) for symptomatic malrotation due to the risk of midgut volvulus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Barium enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Emergency laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A trial of H2, blockade and cisapride therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Overnight pH probe analysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b) This child has malrotation and is at risk for midgut volvulus based on the imaging findings. Typical** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
