  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the duodenum doubles, Trisomy 21 often troubles.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A and C are correct. Duodenal atresia is frequently associated with Trisomy 21, and its typical presentation involves bilious vomiting because the obstruction is usually distal to the ampulla of Vater.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal atresia results from a failure of recanalization of the duodenal lumen during fetal development. The strong association with Trisomy 21 (20-40% of cases) necessitates routine karyotyping and cardiac evaluation (ECHO) due to co-existing congenital heart disease. The characteristic bilious vomiting arises because the obstruction typically occurs distal to the ampulla of Vater, allowing bile to enter the duodenum before encountering the blockage. This leads to the classic 'double bubble' sign on imaging, representing a dilated stomach and proximal duodenum.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Division of an annular pancreas is inappropriate for duodenal obstruction. The duodenum is almost always atretic in addition to the annular pancreas, and dividing the pancreatic tissue risks transecting the accessory pancreatic duct, leading to a pancreatic fistula.\nOption D (Incorrect): The preferred reconstruction for duodenal atresia is a diamond-shaped duodenoduodenostomy, which minimizes the length of defunctionalized duodenum. A Roux-en-Y duodenojejunostomy is not the best or typical approach and is only occasionally considered for very distal duodenal lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Duodenal Atresia | Jejunoileal Atresia |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Failure of recanalization | Ischemic event (e.g., vascular accident) |\n| Vomiting | Bilious (usually) | Bilious |\n| Abdominal Distention | Epigastric ('double bubble') | Generalized |\n| Associated Anomalies | Trisomy 21 (20-40%), CHD, malrotation | Cystic Fibrosis (less common), gastroschisis |\n| Surgical Repair | Diamond-shaped duodenoduodenostomy | Resection of atretic segment, primary anastomosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Double bubble, bilious vomit, Trisomy 21: think duodenal atresia.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe classic 'double bubble' sign on plain abdominal X-ray, representing dilated stomach and proximal duodenum, is pathognomonic. The provided image ![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_20.png) likely depicts this finding. Intraoperatively, the atretic segment is bypassed, typically with a diamond-shaped duodenoduodenostomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) provides recommendations for the management of congenital gastrointestinal anomalies, including duodenal atresia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 20% to 40% of these infants have Trisomy 21 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | When associated with an annular pancreas, division of the pancreas at the s | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bilious vomiting is typical because the obstruction is usually distal to th | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Reconstruction is best achieved with Roux-en-Y duodenojejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c) Twenty to 40% of infants with congenital duodenal obstruction have Trisomy 21. Because this syndrome** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
