  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Glucose first, brain always wins!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. For a 6-week-old presenting with symptomatic hypoglycemia (seizures, glucose 30 mg/dL) and hyperinsulinemia, the immediate priority is to stabilize blood glucose levels to prevent irreversible neurological damage. This is best achieved through continuous glucose infusion via permanent central venous access.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe clinical scenario describes congenital hyperinsulinism, most commonly nesidioblastosis in this age group. The primary goal is to maintain blood glucose above 40 mg/dL. Hypertonic glucose solutions are required, often in high concentrations and volumes, necessitating reliable and long-term intravenous access. A permanent central venous catheter provides this stability, minimizing peripheral line complications and ensuring consistent glucose delivery, which is critical for preventing brain injury in an infant with severe, persistent hypoglycemia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Administration of cortisone and adrenocorticotropic hormone are medical treatments for hyperinsulinism, but they are not the *first priority* over immediate glucose infusion to correct life-threatening hypoglycemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): A computerized tomographic scan of the abdomen to look for an islet cell adenoma is a diagnostic step, but it is not the *first priority*. Stabilizing the patient's glucose is paramount before pursuing definitive diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Urgent pancreatic resection is a definitive surgical treatment for nesidioblastosis or an adenoma, but it is not the *first priority*. Medical stabilization with glucose infusion must precede any surgical intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| **Islet Cell Adenoma (Older Child)** | Glucose infusion                                 | Enucleation or partial pancreatectomy               | Focal lesion, less common in infants                                     |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stabilize glucose first in pediatric hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT scan of the abdomen might be performed to differentiate between diffuse nesidioblastosis (often normal or subtle findings) and a focal islet cell adenoma (a discrete mass), but it is not the initial life-saving step.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Society for Paediatric Endocrinology (ESPE) and Congenital Hyperinsulinism International (CHI) Guidelines for the Management of Congenital Hyperinsulinism (2018) recommend immediate glucose infusion to maintain euglycemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Permanent central venous access and glucose infusion | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Administration of cortisone and adrenocorticotropic hormone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Computerized tomographic scan of the abdomen to look for an islet cell aden | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Urgent pancreatic resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Most cases of hyperinsulinemia in the first 2 years of life are due to nesidioblastosis, a condition** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
