  "answer": "B) ![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_28.png)\nUndescended testis occurs in 30% of premature boys, 3.4% of full-term boys, 0.8% of 1-year olds, and 0.8% of adults. The implication is that if spontaneous testicular descent has not occurred by 1 year of age, it is unlikely to occur subsequently. Therefore, orchiopexy is deferred until the patient reaches 1 year of age. Testes that remain undescended during childhood have a significant reduction in the number of germ cells and have little function after puberty. Demonstrable histologic changes are present by the age of 2 years. For this reason, delay beyond 1 year is not recommended.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 One year: the sweet spot for testicular descent.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 1 year. Surgical orchiopexy is recommended around 1 year of age for a unilateral undescended testis because spontaneous descent is unlikely after this point, and delaying surgery beyond this age can lead to irreversible testicular damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe rationale for performing orchiopexy around 1 year of age is multifactorial. While spontaneous descent can occur in the first few months of life, it is highly improbable after 6 months to 1 year. Delaying surgery beyond 1 year leads to progressive and irreversible histological changes in the germ cells, impacting future fertility potential. Studies show a significant reduction in germ cell count and function by 2 years of age. Early intervention aims to preserve fertility, reduce the risk of malignancy (though not entirely eliminated), and prevent complications like torsion or trauma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Promptly upon discovery, regardless of age) (Incorrect): This is incorrect because a period of observation (typically up to 6 months, sometimes 1 year) is warranted to allow for potential spontaneous testicular descent.\nOption C (5 to 6 years) (Incorrect): This is too late. Significant and irreversible histological damage to the germ cells would have already occurred by this age, severely compromising fertility potential.\nOption D (Any time prior to puberty) (Incorrect): While surgery should ideally occur before puberty, this option is too broad and allows for significant delays that would result in irreversible testicular damage and reduced fertility.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Incidence** | 3.4% in full-term boys, 0.8% at 1 year |\n| **Spontaneous Descent** | Unlikely after 1 year of age |\n| **Recommended Surgery Age** | 6-12 months (ideally by 1 year) |\n| **Risks of Delay** | Irreversible germ cell damage, reduced fertility, increased cancer risk, torsion, trauma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Orchiopexy at 1 year to save the germ cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgical exploration, the undescended testis may be found anywhere along its normal path of descent, from the retroperitoneum to the inguinal canal or even ectopically. The surgeon will mobilize the testis and spermatic cord to bring the testis into the scrotum without tension, securing it within a dartos pouch.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) 2014 Guideline: The AUA recommends surgical correction for cryptorchidism between 6 and 12 months of age.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Promptly upon discovery, regardless of age | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 1 year | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 5 to 6 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Any time prior to puberty | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_28.png)\nUndescended testis occurs in 30** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
