  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neuroblastoma: N-myc is bad news for little ones.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key epidemiological and prognostic factors for neuroblastoma. Neuroblastoma is indeed the most common abdominal malignancy of childhood, with the majority of patients diagnosed before age 4. Furthermore, N-myc oncogene copy number is a critical prognostic indicator, inversely related to survival.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma is a highly heterogeneous tumor, and understanding its epidemiology and molecular markers is crucial for risk stratification and treatment planning. The high incidence in young children (80% before age 4) underscores the importance of early diagnosis in pediatric oncology. N-myc amplification is a well-established marker of aggressive disease and poor prognosis, driving more intensive therapy. Conversely, TrkA expression is generally associated with a more differentiated tumor and a favorable outcome, highlighting the complex interplay of molecular pathways in this disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Trk proto-oncogene expression (specifically TrkA) in neuroblastoma tissue is generally *directly* related to survival probability, meaning higher expression is associated with a *favorable* prognosis, not inversely. TrkB and TrkC can have different implications.\nOption E (Incorrect): Since option D is incorrect, 'All of the above' cannot be true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Prognostic Implication |\n|---|---|\n| N-myc amplification | Poor prognosis (aggressive disease) |\n| TrkA expression | Favorable prognosis (more differentiated) |\n| Age at diagnosis (<1 year) | Favorable prognosis |\n| Stage 4S | Favorable prognosis (often spontaneous regression) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: N-myc bad, TrkA good, young age good for neuroblastoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), neuroblastoma typically presents as a heterogeneous, often calcified, suprarenal mass that frequently crosses the midline and encases vessels. Intraoperatively, it can be firm, nodular, and highly vascular, often with extensive local invasion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (e.g., ANBL1232, ANBL1531) recommend risk stratification based on age, stage, N-myc amplification, and other molecular markers to guide treatment intensity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Neuroblastoma is the most common abdominal malignancy of childhood | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Approximately 80% of neuroblastoma patients are diagnosed prior to age 4 ye | ✅ Correct |\n| C | N-myc oncogene copy number in neuroblastoma tissue is inversely related to  | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Trk proto-oncogene expression in neuroblastoma tissue is inversely related  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) Neuroblastoma is the most common extracranial solid tumor and the most common abdominal malignancy o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
