  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neuroblastoma's risk is in the details, especially for the young.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies several key low-risk features for neuroblastoma, a common extracranial solid tumor in childhood. The correct answer encompasses age, specific disease stages, and biochemical markers, all of which are crucial for prognostic stratification and treatment planning.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma risk stratification is complex, integrating clinical, pathological, and molecular features. Age less than one year is a favorable prognostic factor, often associated with less aggressive disease. Stage 2A/2B disease represents localized tumors that are resectable or partially resectable, indicating a lower burden. Stage 4S (Special) is unique to infants under 18 months, characterized by metastatic disease to liver, skin, or bone marrow (without cortical bone involvement) that frequently undergoes spontaneous regression, hence its low-risk designation. A lower plasma level of Neuron Specific Enolase (NSE), a tumor marker, correlates with a smaller tumor burden and better prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption E (Incorrect): \"None of the above\" is incorrect because options A, B, C, and D all represent established low-risk features for neuroblastoma patients, indicating a favorable prognosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Low Risk | High Risk |\n|---|---|---|\n| Age | < 18 months (especially < 1 year) | >= 18 months |\n| Stage | 1, 2, 4S | 3, 4 |\n| MYCN Amplification | Absent | Present |\n| Histology | Favorable | Unfavorable |\n| Ploidy | Hyperdiploid | Diploid |\n| NSE | Low (<100 ng/ml) | High (>100 ng/ml) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Age, stage, and MYCN define neuroblastoma risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), neuroblastoma typically appears as an irregular, heterogeneous mass, often calcified, arising from the adrenal gland or sympathetic chain. Intraoperatively, it's a firm, often lobulated tumor, frequently encasing vessels, making complete resection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Neuroblastoma Risk Group Staging System (INRGSS) 2009. It provides a comprehensive system for risk stratification based on clinical, imaging, and biological factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Age less than one year | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stage 2A and 2B disease (International Staging Criteria) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stage 4S disease (International Staging Criteria) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neuron specific enolase plasma level less than 100 ng/ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c, d) Risk status is determined in neuroblastoma patients by a number of characteristics which have been e** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
