  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Grapes in the vagina? Think rhabdomyosarcoma, not fruit salad!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic presentation of a friable, polypoid mass prolapsing through the vaginal introitus in a one-month-old female infant, which is highly characteristic of the botryoid subtype.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEmbryonal rhabdomyosarcoma, specifically the botryoid subtype, commonly presents as a friable, grape-like polypoid mass prolapsing from hollow organs such as the vagina or bladder. This tumor exhibits a biphasic incidence, with a notable peak in infancy, making it a critical consideration in this age group. Its friable nature often leads to hemorrhage, which aligns with the clinical description of a friable mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ectopic ureterocele) (Incorrect): An ectopic ureterocele typically presents as a smooth, cystic, non-friable mass, often associated with urinary symptoms, not a friable polypoid mass.\nOption B (Rectal prolapse) (Incorrect): Rectal prolapse involves eversion of rectal mucosa, appearing as concentric rings, and originates from the anus, not the vaginal introitus, and is not friable in this manner.\nOption C (Congenital adrenal hyperplasia with ambiguous genitalia) (Incorrect): CAH causes hormonal imbalances leading to virilization and ambiguous genitalia, but it does not manifest as a prolapsing friable polypoid mass from the vagina.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Vaginal Botryoid Rhabdomyosarcoma | Ectopic Ureterocele | Rectal Prolapse |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Appearance** | Friable, polypoid, \"grape-like\" mass | Smooth, cystic, non-friable mass | Concentric rings of rectal mucosa |\n| **Location** | Prolapsing from vaginal introitus | Prolapsing from urethra/vagina (often cystic) | Prolapsing from anus |\n| **Consistency** | Friable, may bleed | Soft, fluid-filled | Soft, mucosal |\n| **Age of Onset** | Infancy (biphasic peak) | Infancy/childhood | Infancy/childhood |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A friable vaginal polyp in an infant is rhabdomyosarcoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound, MRI), a botryoid rhabdomyosarcoma would appear as an irregular, often heterogeneous, polypoid mass filling and protruding from the vaginal lumen. Intraoperatively, it presents as a soft, friable, grape-like mass. The provided image clearly depicts a friable, polypoid mass prolapsing through the vaginal introitus, consistent with this diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) guidelines for Rhabdomyosarcoma (e.g., ARST1431) recommend a comprehensive staging workup including imaging (MRI, CT, PET), bone marrow biopsy, and surgical biopsy for diagnosis and risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ectopic ureterocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rectal prolapse | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Congenital adrenal hyperplasia with ambiguous genitalia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: d) Vaginal and cervical primary rhabdomyosarcomas often prolapse through the vaginal orifice as a friab** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
