  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Shrink it to resect it, then they can live it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights a critical principle in hepatoblastoma management: the use of neoadjuvant chemotherapy to downstage initially unresectable tumors. This strategy allows for subsequent complete surgical resection, which is the most important prognostic factor for long-term survival in these pediatric patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatoblastoma is a highly chemosensitive tumor. Neoadjuvant chemotherapy, typically with cisplatin-based regimens, is often employed to reduce tumor size and volume. This downstaging can convert an initially unresectable tumor into one that is amenable to complete surgical removal (R0 resection). Achieving an R0 resection significantly improves long-term survival rates, which can exceed 80% with a multidisciplinary approach involving chemotherapy and surgery. This multimodal strategy is fundamental to modern hepatoblastoma treatment protocols.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Multicentricity is uncommon in hepatoblastoma, occurring in less than 20% of cases. It is a more characteristic feature of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC).\nOption B (Incorrect): Cirrhosis in the uninvolved liver is unusual in hepatoblastoma. This finding is more typically associated with hepatocellular carcinoma, especially in adults or older children with underlying liver disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Jaundice is an uncommon presenting symptom for hepatoblastoma. Patients typically present with an abdominal mass, and liver function tests are often normal or non-specifically altered.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Hepatoblastoma                                     | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) (Pediatric)             |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Age**             | Typically <3 years (most common pediatric liver tumor) | Older children/adolescents, often with underlying liver disease |\n| **Multicentricity** | Uncommon (<20%), usually single lesion           | More common, especially with underlying liver disease  |\n| **Cirrhosis**       | Unusual in surrounding liver                       | Often associated with underlying cirrhosis             |\n| **Jaundice**        | Uncommon                                           | Can be present, especially with advanced disease       |\n| **AFP**             | Elevated in ~90% of cases                          | Elevated in many cases, but can be normal              |\n| **Chemosensitivity**| Highly chemosensitive (neoadjuvant therapy common) | Less chemosensitive, primary resection preferred if possible |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neoadjuvant chemotherapy can make unresectable hepatoblastomas resectable, improving survival.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question includes an image tag `![Image](/images/review_bank/763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq_32.png)`. On imaging (e.g., CT or MRI), hepatoblastomas typically appear as a large, solitary, well-circumscribed, pseudo-encapsulated mass, often with heterogeneous enhancement and possible calcifications. Intraoperatively, these tumors are usually firm, well-demarcated, and can be quite large, sometimes occupying a significant portion of the liver.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) AHEP1431 (or similar contemporary protocols) Guidelines for Hepatoblastoma (updated periodically) recommend neoadjuvant chemotherapy for most patients, especially those with advanced or initially unresectable disease, to facilitate complete surgical resection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Multicentricity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cirrhosis in the uninvolved liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Unresectable tumors subjected to cytoreductive chemotherapy may be resected | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Jaundice | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c) Children with hepatoblastoma most commonly present with an abdominal mass or diffuse abdominal swell** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
