  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bone and marrow are neuroblastoma's favorite travel destinations.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies regional lymph nodes, bone marrow, and cortical bone as common sites of neuroblastoma metastasis. This is accurate because neuroblastoma frequently spreads to these locations, with bone marrow and cortical bone being particularly characteristic and prognostically significant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma is a highly metastatic tumor, often presenting with disseminated disease at diagnosis. Its predilection for bone marrow and cortical bone is a hallmark, distinguishing it from many other pediatric malignancies. Metastasis to regional lymph nodes is also common, reflecting local spread. The involvement of cortical bone, as detected by bone scan, is a significant poor prognostic indicator, highlighting the aggressive nature of the disease when it reaches this stage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Lung) (Incorrect): The lungs are a rare site for neuroblastoma metastasis, unlike many other solid tumors. The provided answer key explicitly states that lungs are rarely the site of metastatic spread.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metastatic Site | Frequency in Neuroblastoma | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Regional Lymph Nodes | Common | Indicates local/regional spread |\n| Bone Marrow | Very Common | Major site of distant metastasis |\n| Cortical Bone | Common | Poor prognostic indicator, often detected by bone scan |\n| Liver | Less Common | More frequent in infants, especially stage 4S |\n| Lung | Rare | Infrequent site of distant metastasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neuroblastoma loves bone and marrow, not lung.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, bone marrow involvement might be seen as diffuse signal changes on MRI or uptake on MIBG scans. Cortical bone metastasis is typically identified by increased uptake on technetium-99m bone scans or MIBG scans, appearing as focal lesions. Intraoperatively, enlarged, firm regional lymph nodes might be noted.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive staging and treatment recommendations, including assessment of metastatic sites.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lung | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regional lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bone marrow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cortical bone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, c, d) Neuroblastoma metastasizes to both regional lymph nodes and distant sites, most frequently bone marr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 763833961-pediatric-surgery-mcq.pdf**\n",
